				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-7678857#post-4139175</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-7678857/scp-4950#post-4139175</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Sat, 02 Feb 2019 13:52:34 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>PeppersGhost</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>1553042</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>I usually hate articles that portray an overly magic-savvy Foundation with Anti-Magic Science Things, but it can still work for me if the article doesn't take itself too seriously, so it works perfectly for this story. With the overall tongue-in-cheek tone, things like &quot;automatic exorcists&quot; feel like nuggets of wry humor peppered onto the joke, rather than a series of narrative cop-outs.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-7678857#post-4139056</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-7678857/scp-4950#post-4139056</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Sat, 02 Feb 2019 09:57:55 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Quasibenevolence</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>5140935</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>The Foundation handling threats realistically with basic competence literally helps soothe the headache some of the stories on this site can give me. Also, the use of repeated phrases is a cornerstone of historical magical practice and geeky slogans or memes are perfectly fine fodder for the same. IMO, there’s nothing overly trendy or hip about using memes this way. (I’m reminded of an In Nomine character that sought Lucifer’s blessing by fulfilling a ritual requiring millions of chant repetitions with a modern, popular song.)</p> <p>Solid, +1.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
